# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

I will explain two things 

**1) How do we start thinking when we such questions**

**2) How do i write code for such a thing...**

Answer 1) 

You are given a string , let us say **s="Leetcode"** and your **array = ["leet , "code","shit"]**

Now, how do i start, 

Remember this rule, When you can't understand where to start, **just break the string in the lowest size possible...**

SO, here Let us break..Leetcode into smallest size possible ..**that is "L", "e" , "e" ,"t" "c", "o", "d" ,"e"**...Are any of the chactarcters present in your array ... **your ans is  no**

Now, let us move to the second smallest size possible .. that is..**"le","ee" ,"et" , "tc" ,"co" ,"od" , "de"**..Are any of the strings presnt in your array..**The ans is no..**

Now, Let us move to the **fourth smallest size possible**..that is **"leet", "eetc"...and so on..**.

Now , you found **that atleast leet is present in your array**, Now once you find that** atleast somnething is presnt** ..we will start **forming strings again from the next index onwards..**

Let me explain , After leet, we will again form **strings of size 1..****then 2 ..then 3 and so on.**..Let us say you again **find a string of size 4 which is present so**..you will again start the same process from the next index....

**Now, how do we write the code for such a thing ...**

```
        string x;
        bool ans  = false;

        for(int k=i; k<s.size(); k++)
        {
            x+=s[k];

            if(jd.find(x)!=jd.end())
            {
                ans = check(k+1,s,jd,dp);
                if(ans==true)
                {
                    dp[i] = 1;
