# Approach
I used an advanced data structure that can detect matches in one-pass. This data structure is called Aho-Corasick automaton. The present solutions in leetcode are at $$O(n^2)$$ solution. This solution runs at $$O(k + m)$$ at test time with an overhead of $$O(n)$$. I hope this helps you impress your future interviewer. (◍•ᴗ•◍)
# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n + k + m)$$
Build Automaton: $$O(n)$$ where $$n$$ is the total number of characters in the dictionary.
Test segmentation: $$O(k + m)$$ where $$k$$ is the length of string to segment and $$m$$ represents the number of matches present between the dictionary and the string to segment.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n + m)$$
Automaton: $$O(n + m)$$
DP Array: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


# Code
```python
class TrieNode:
    def __init__(self):
        self.children = defaultdict(TrieNode)
        self.fail = None
        self.output = set()


class AhoCorasick:
    def __init__(self, words):
        self.root = TrieNode()
        self.build_trie(words)
        self.build_fail()

    def build_trie(self, words):
        for word in words:
            curr = self.root
            for c in word:
                curr = curr.children[c]
            curr.output.add(word)

    def build_fail(self):
        q = deque([self.root])
        while q:
            curr = q.popleft()
            for n, child in list(curr.children.items()):
                if curr is self.root:
                    child.fail = curr
                else:
                    p = curr.fail
                    while p is not self.root and n not in p.children:
                        p = p.fail
                    if n in p.children:
                        p = p.children[n]
                    child.fail = p
                    child.output.update(p.output)
                q.append(child)


class Solution:
    def wordBreak(self, s: str, wordDict: List[str]) -> bool:
        ac = AhoCorasick(wordDict)
        n = len(s)
        dp = [False] * (n + 1)
        dp[0] = True
        curr = ac.root
        for i in range(n):
            c = s[i]
            while curr is not ac.root and c not in curr.children:
                curr = curr.fail
            if c in curr.children:
                curr = curr.children[c]
            else:
                return False

            for word in curr.output:
                start = i - len(word) + 1
                dp[i + 1] = dp[start] or dp[i + 1]
                if dp[i + 1]: break

        return dp[-1]

```

