# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We are trying to partition the string in the best possible way.
For a particular index we're trying to find the maximum length of the string that can be formed from the current index that is present in the dictionary.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Since the recursive solution would have a exponential complexity, we'll be using memoization and bring it down to O(n) (n=given string length).
We've further optimized our searching time by using hashmap.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    O(n)

- Space complexity:
 m=wordDict size hashmap, n=given string length
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
    O(n+m)
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int fun(int ind,string&s,unordered_map<string,int>&mp,vector<int>&dp) 
    {
        if(ind==s.length()) 
         return 0;
        if(dp[ind]!=-1) 
         return dp[ind];
        string tmp="";
        int len=0; 
        for(int j=ind;j<s.length();j++) 
        {
            tmp+=s[j]; 
            if(mp[tmp]) 
            {   
                len=max(len,(j-ind+1)+fun(j+1,s,mp,dp));
            }   
        } 
        return dp[ind]=len;
    }
    bool wordBreak(string s, vector<string>& wordDict) {
        unordered_map<string,int>mp;
        for(auto it:wordDict) 
            mp[it]++;
        int n=s.length();
            vector<int>dp(n,-1);
        return fun(0,s,mp,dp)==s.length();
    }
};
```

