solutions.content:
**Intuition**
Both approaches attempt to create a substring starting from a particular position, and when a word from the dictionary is identified, they branch out to explore alternate paths from the next index.

First, I tried the `recursive approach` which was easier to reason about.

**Recursive Approach**

```c++
class Solution {
public:
    bool wordBreak(string s, vector<string>& dict) {
        unordered_set<string> bag(dict.begin(), dict.end());
        unordered_map<int, bool> cache;

        // Define a recursive function to solve the problem
        function<bool(int)> go = [&](auto start) {
            // Base case: if we have reached the end of the string, return true
            if (start == s.size()) return true;
            // Check if we have already solved this subproblem
            if (cache.count(start)) return cache[start];

            // Otherwise, try all possible ways to split the string from the current position
            bool is_possible = false;
            string builder = "";
            for (int i = start; i < s.size(); i++) {
                builder += s[i];
                if (bag.count(builder)) is_possible |= go(i + 1);
            }
            // Memoize the result of this subproblem and return it
            return cache[start] = is_possible;
        };

        // Solve the problem starting from the beginning of the string
        return go(0);
    }
};
```

However, as the recursive approach was slower, I converted it to iterative resulting in 96% faster solution.

**Iterative Approach**

```c++
class Solution {
public:
    bool wordBreak(string s, vector<string>& dict) {
        unordered_set<string> bag(dict.begin(), dict.end());

        // Create a vector of boolean values, initialized to false, 
        // to store whether a substring of s can be broken into words
        vector<bool> dp(s.size() + 1, false);

        // Set the value of dp[0] to true, as an empty string can always be broken into words
        dp[0] = true;

        // Create a queue to store the starting index of the substring to be processed
        queue<int> q; q.push(0);

        // Loop through the queue until it is empty
        while (q.size()) {
            // Get the starting index of the next substring to be processed
            auto start = q.front(); q.pop();

            // If we've processed the entire string, skip
            if (start == s.size()) continue;

            // Create a string to store the current substring being built
            string builder = "";

            // Loop through the remaining characters of s, starting from the current index
            for (int i = start; i < s.size(); i++) {
                // Add the current character to the builder string
                builder += s[i];

                // If the builder string is in the dictionary, and the previous substring (dp[start]) 
                // can be broken into words, and the current substring has not been processed yet (not dp[i + 1]), 
                // mark the current substring as being able to be broken into words, and add the 
                // starting index of the next substring to the queue to be processed later
                if (bag.count(builder) && dp[start] && !dp[i + 1]) {
                    q.push(i + 1);
                    dp[i + 1] = true;
                }
            }
        }

        // Return the value of the last element of the dp array, which represents whether 
        // the entire string can be broken into words
        return dp[s.size()];
    }
};
```

