This is a popular question. To solve this, a more intuitive solution is recursion. But a trivial recurstion will return TLE, which is not accepted. We can apply a memorized recursion here to reduce the time complexity, to which is acceptable.

It is worth to note that, memorized recursion can be deemed as a top down dynamic programming solution. Then we can also propose a bottom up dynamic programming solution, which is the solution 2 below.
```
class Solution {
    public boolean wordBreak(String s, List<String> wordDict) {
	// Solution 1: Memorized Recursion
         Set<String> set = new HashSet<>();
         Map<String, Boolean> map = new HashMap<>();
         for (String a : wordDict) {
             set.add(a);
         }
         return canBreak(s, set, map);
     }

     public boolean canBreak(String s, Set<String> set, Map<String, Boolean> map) {
         if (map.containsKey(s)) return map.get(s);
         if (set.contains(s)) {
             map.put(s, true);
             return true;
         }
         for (int i=0; i<s.length(); i++) {
             if (set.contains(s.substring(0, i+1)) && canBreak(s.substring(i+1, s.length()), set, map)) {
                 map.put(s.substring(i+1, s.length()), true);
                 return true;
             }                
         }
         map.put(s, false);
         return false;
	}
}

