# Saving Space

This approach definitely uses a significant amount of memory if `wordDict` is very large since we store a copy each `word` in `wordDict` in our map, but we can fix this problem if we store the index of each `word` in the original `wordDict` array rather than the `word` itself. Because we no longer store a copy of the words in `wordDict`, our space complexity is reduced to $O(l + m)$ ($l$ is the length of ```s``` and $m$ is the length of the dictionary) and the time complexity remains the same.

```
class Solution {
public:
    bool wordBreak(string s, vector<string>& wordDict) {

        unordered_map<char, vector<int>> insertions;
        vector<bool> dp(s.size() + 1, false);
        int nxt;

        dp[s.size()] = true;

        for (int i = 0; i < wordDict.size(); ++i)
            insertions[wordDict[i][0]].push_back(i);

        for (int i = s.size() - 1; i > -1; --i)
        {
            for (int pos : insertions[s[i]])
            {
                nxt = i + wordDict[pos].size();
                if (nxt <= s.size() && dp[nxt] && s.compare(i, wordDict[pos].size(), wordDict[pos]) == 0)
                {
                    dp[i] = true;
                    break;
                }
            }
        }

        return dp[0];
    }
};
```

# Approach
So I have seen many DP Solutions here.
Instead of DP I used normal BFS but with Set,
Basically what DP does here is to avoid the same computation at a given index being queried multiple times due to recursion (worst case exponential)....so you use DP so as the queries are only entertained once and convert it into n^2 time (for n=string length).

Basically I kept this same concept in mind and Made a set which records partitions already pushed in queue once and so to not to compute them further every time they are added in queue due to various possible ways to reach there for a partition.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(N*maxlenofstr+(maxlenofstr)^2)

- Space complexity:
O(N*maxlenofstr)

# Code
