# Intuition
In the problem, we employ a double-ended queue (deque) to track the indices of potential maximum elements within sliding windows of size k as they traverse the input vector nums. By maintaining a deque that stores only relevant indices, removing unnecessary elements, and ensuring that the maximum candidate elements are consistently positioned at the front of the deque, we identify the maximum element for each window and populate the result vector. 
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
- We use a deque q to store the indices of potential maximum elements within the window.
- For each element in nums, we:
- - Remove elements from the front of q that are no longer in the current window.
- - Remove elements from the back of q that are smaller than the current element.
- Add the current element's index to the back of q.
- If the window size is equal to k, add the maximum element (at the front of q) to the result vector.
- Return the result vector containing maximum elements for each window.
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(k)
